class Solution {
public:
    bool isValid(string s) {
        stack<char> brackets;
        for (char c : s) {
            if (c == '(' || c == '[' || c == '{') {
                brackets.push(c);
            } else {
                if (brackets.empty() || brackets.top() != c) {
                    return false;
                }
                brackets.pop();
            }
        }
        return brackets.empty();
    }
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n), where n is the length of the string
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

The solution uses a stack data structure to keep track of the opening brackets encountered. It iterates through the string character by character. For each character, if it is an opening bracket, it pushes it into the stack. If it is a closing bracket, it checks if the top element of the stack matches the closing bracket and pops it from the stack. If the stack is empty or the popped element does not match the closing bracket, the function returns false. Otherwise, it returns true when the stack is empty, indicating that all brackets have been properly matched.

